< review>
About 10 months ago I had to make one of the biggest hardest to decide decisions of my life... I needed complete dentures, and at the age of 82 I really didn't know if I was ready to make a huge commitment like that.... Pain????  money???? permanent relief and ability to eat normally ???   All major questions... With wonderful loving advice from family and consultations with Dr. Slaughter, I felt comfortable and confident with the decision to invest in myself and my comfort... It has been 10 months and I can honestly say it was an easy journey.... Dr. Slaughter and his staff were so calm, reassuring, and there anytime I had a question during the aftercare...They simply did not allow me to be apprehensive...I am now 100% confident with my dentures, no more pain from bad bad teeth, and I cannot tell the difference in my dentures and how my real teeth used to feel... I am eating normally, (even corn on the cob)....So I highly recommend this pleasant professional office...

Virginia Klippness</review>

<userid>105642641163099168852<//userid><Name>Keleigh Walbrecht<//Name>< date>
1490502384911</date>
< rating>
1<//rating>
< text>
DO NOT USE DOCTOR SLAUGHTER. I AM STILL SUFFERING FROM HIS MISTAKE.

I got my wisdom teeth extracted by Doctor Slaughter in late July of summer 2016. It is now March 2017, and I just had my second surgery to fix things that could have avoided in the first place if he did the surgery right. A week after I had my wisdom teeth taken out, I got an infection so I was put on a small dose of antibiotic by Slaughter. A week or so later I had finished the antibiotic and left the country for a vacation. My first night in Belize, I woke up and the infection had gotten very bad. That morning I went to a doctor in the nearest town and he had to squeeze the infection out with his hands because it was so bad. He then put me on a stronger antibiotic (what Slaughter should have put me on in the first place) and it killed most of the infection. When I got back home, I went back to Slaughter and he found a piece of dead bone that he left in. He thought nothing of it.

Fast forward to 8 months later and I am still having severe pain. I went into an oral surgeons office a couple weeks ago and he said from the looks of it, there was still an infection. Yesterday, March 24th I had a biopsy and they found a piece of root from my wisdom tooth that had been left in there!!! It was causing a serious infection to where my bone was very soft and mushy.

3 surgeries when this could have been avoided if done correctly. Doctor Slaughter is definitely not a good option if you are looking for an oral surgeon.</text>

<rating>5</rating>< text>
I hope Dr. WILSON and his staff read this !!!!

I think Dr. WILSON is one of the best doctors/dentists who has ever treated me in my entire lifetime and I will b 66 on 11/11/2018. U can tell he really cares about his patients cuz he asks how I am feeling & actually waits & listens to my response all the while he looks me in the eyes. He does not act so busy as if I am wasting his precious time. I happen to know that this is quite rare for medical professionals these days because approx. 2 weeks after my oral surgery w/ Wilson I had another surgery & this surgeon moved, talked & reacted so quickly that it made me nervous & uncomfortable & scared. This surgeon had a much larger support team but somehow I felt like I was just another patient in a long line of scheduled surgeries. Dr. Wilson called me himself and also one of his staff following my procedure to "check in on me ". WOW ! THAT IS A VERY KIND & CONSIDERATE THING TO DO. OF COARSE NO PHONE CALL FROM THE OTHER SURGEON NOR ANY OF HIS STAFF. The pre-op instructions from the other surgeon included 4 simple things: 1. Hav responsible adult pick up after surgery. 2. Wear short sleeves & comfortable clothing. 3. Bring pillow to elevate arm following surgery. 4. Directions to surgicenter (map & written directions) which I found most helpful. But nothing about not eating/drinking b4 procedure which I knew I had to do from Dr. WILSON'S PRE-OP INSTRUCTIONS. I TOLD THE RECEPTIONIST AT THE OTHER OFFICE THAT PRE-OP INSTRUCTIONS WERE MINIMAL & SHE SAID MANY PATIENTS TELL HER THAT. HELLO ? THEN WHY NOT CHANGE THEM. WHEN I WENT IN FOR THE SURGERY THEY ASKED ME WHEN IT WAS THAT I last ate. What wld hav happened if I said 3 hours ago? SHEEZ!!! And the final thing Dr. WILSON DID WHICH I really appreciated was explain all of my options. Now how many times has a physician/dentist done this for you ? Very knowledgeable, organized, positive and great sense of humor-all things that helped me feel relaxed and comfortable. And his staff fills in just where needed. I highly recommend Dr. WILSON to anyone requiring oral surgery. I NEVER KNEW I CLD MAIL MY FILLINGS & RECEIVE CASH. AND I HAV HAD MANY MANY MANY FILLINGS THROUGHOUT MY LIFETIME. THAT WAS A BONUS BONUS BONUS. IT FELT LIKE I HIT THE JACKPOT. THANKS DOCTOR & TEAM! I REALLY APPRECIATE HOW COMFORTABLE YOU MADE ME FEEL.< /text>

< review>
This is my first week along with my daughter and we have been so impressed!  Tower Yoga has such a great vibe!  Starting with Jamison who signed us up and then let my other daughter have a trial run.  The facility itself is amazing from offering free face towels to all the supplies provided in the bathroom. Tower Yoga IS all about connectedness and building community. Because of all the accolades and raves we speak about Tower Yoga now my oldest daughter wants to join too!  This is my first yoga membership after trying other programs and just after a week I know this is something I need for my mental health and will continue. The instructors are amazing and passionate about what they do.  Today during the 11am class was especially difficult for me because we buried my best friend's father who was also my godfather.  I broke down and cried as I was leaving and Crystal was so kind and talked to me with such compassion that my feelings of embarrassment quickly dissolved and I embraced my tears. Crystal talked about how that self awareness is healing and happens with yoga.   When she said "cry it out sista" I knew she meant it.  I am very grateful to share how much I appreciate Tower Yoga and all the people who make it a welcoming and peaceful place.  Thank you for asking!<//review>

< text>
I have EXTREME dental-anything anxiety because I was traumatized by Dr. Wells, my East Orange,  New Jersey dentist from the 60's.  Novacain needles were huge, and there was no gentle approach with use of a topical anesthetic to lessen that little "pinch" dentists say we will feel.  My sisters and I went to the same dentist as our parents, not taken to a pediatric dentist, so our tears did not resonate.  Fast forward to 5 decades later, and I am still a basket case in any dental procedure chair.  Thank goodness for the compassionate and exceptional staff and endodontists at Endo Care. If I could give 10 stars, I would give 110.  For real.</text>

<rating>5<//rating><GmapID>0x808f8695c6feaa9b:0x4ea728f016db8fbd<//GmapID>< Text>
When my crown fell off it exposed an old root canal and in order to avoid infection, my dentist referred me to EndoCare for a thorough evaluation of my tooth base. I went to the EndoCare Alameda office and easily found street parking. I was greeted by Jennifer, their friendly receptionist, and completed general medical information forms. Diane welcomed me and expertly completed preliminary X-rays, then also provided me details of my treatment prep on my follow up appointment. On the day of the evaluation, I received clear information from Dr. Alyson Barnes on how to save my tooth and I returned in a few days for the root canal treatment. Dr. Barnes has a steady and skilled hand for painless injecting of novocaine and drilling. Dr. Barnes and Diane alerted me to changes in procedures during the treatment to ease my nerves. This care for patient comfort was much appreciated. I took three 200mg ibuprofen tabs after the treatment just in case but was fine later. If you also get a cold shiver down your spine when you remember past dental treatment experiences, don't delay treating your teeth and see Dr. Barnes.</Text>

<text>I was referred to Dr. Ali Rezai by my dentist, Dr. Dean, in September. I very foolishly delayed making an appointment (always listen to your dental professionals!) and the "shadow" in the root of my molar became an abcess during the Thanksgiving holiday. I made an appointment Wednesday for the following Monday. By Friday I was in excruciating pain and called Dr. Rezai's office. Thank the lucky stars they were open. Although he couldn't treat me that day, he did get me on antibiotics and pain meds until I could have the retreatment done the following week at the Alameda facility.

I met with Dr. Nick Norton and Michelle (who I met in the Oakland office) and they were absolutely wonderful! They put me at ease after I let them know I was a little anxious and that it takes quite a bit anesthetic to numb me properly. Absolutely no pain - the most was the slight pinch from the shot! They were done in a little over an hour and I was on my merry way. The follow-up treatment two weeks later took even less time and again, no pain.

The offices in Oakland and Alameda are very clean and well kept. The front office staff are polite, professional and accommodating and the medical staff and Drs. Rezai and Norton know their specialty ~ I would highly recommend them for anyone undergoing endodontic treatment ~ they are a first rate practice!<//text><Pics>None</Pics><Resp>None<//Resp><Gmap_id>0x808f8695c6feaa9b:0x4ea728f016db8fbd<//Gmap_id></record>

< text>
Latter-day Saints are a temple-building and temple-loving people. It has been so from the earliest days of the Church. Through the Prophet Joseph Smith, the Lord declared that "my people are always commanded to build [temples] In temples, we can draw closer to the Lord, we can learn more about His plan for our happiness, we can receive essential ordinances for our exaltation, and we can perform vicarious service on behalf of those who have died without the gospel of Jesus Christ. The culminating blessing of the temple is that we can be joined together as families for eternity, so that our relationships with those we love will last forever.<//text>

<rating>5</rating>< text>
This temple is visible on the hill above I-5 as you head north towards Los Angeles leaving San Diego.  It is a pure white castle of marble and has been known to many young girls as the princess castle.  The symbolism on the exterior is amazing and I especially love the seal of Melchizedek.  The atrium within the temple is also really amazing.< /text>

<userid>117979392280278344991<//userid>< Text>
One of my favorite temples! The exterior is magnificent, but so is the interior. It's truly a House of the Lord. I've been here for baptisms, weddings, and endowments. It's a great place to stop and take photos even if you're not a member but have a zest for photography and like beautiful buildings. It's probably the most beautiful building in San Diego, and that's saying something.<//Text>

< text>
What a special place this is. Even during the pandemic, just being outside the gate offers peace. This was stunning at night during the Christmas season. If you are looking for a place to feel comfort and light, this is a good place to start. To learn more about this sacred place, you can go to ChurchofJesusChrist.org< /text>

<review>The San Diego temple was located right off the freeway and we kept seeing it as we drove up and down La Jolla. So we decided to stop by and check out the temple.

it is open for guests till it closes and there ample parking available as long as there is no service. it is best to see the temple at night with the lights lit on especially during the holiday periods when they do an exceptional job decorating the trees and the grounds around the temple. <Rating>4</Rating><text>Being raised in Catholic environment, and being influenced to appreciate art and architecture by my architect father, I have always been fascinated by design and architecture of houses of worship. I became fully aware of this when I visited Vatican first time in 1980s.

That being said, when I had opportunity to explore the inside of Tabernacle in Temple Square in Salt Lake City with Mormon friends in mid-1990s, I was thrilled to have the opportunity to explore from the back of the church as the choir rehearsed. It was an amazing and enlightening experience.

I saw California Temple across the freeway on my way to my hotel in San Diego. It was striking contrast to the skyline surrounding it, so we decided to visit a few days later -- not considering that houses of worship have been closed in California due to COVID. Needless to say, I was a bit disappointed we could not explore the inside of this Temple when we arrived, but made the best of it.

It was a challenge to capture this fantastic structure in photographs, but we drove around and found several spots to capture different angles and bits of the building. If given the chance, I would be more than happy to see the inside of the building, walk around the gardens as I believe that it would be just as striking and fascinating as outside.<//text><Pictures>None</Pictures>< response>

<Date>1571410239071<//Date>< Review>
Architecturally, what you get when you cross a Disney castle and a space ship.
For members of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints, this is the area's most sacred place of worship and service---a most welcome refuge from worldly ruckus. For those who are not members, visitors are welcome to view the outside grounds of perhaps the most stunning of The Church's temples.<//Review>

< text>
Beautiful area. Lots of flowers and great places for picture taking. The temple looks good from every angle. It's a sacred place for members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints. There is a small waiting area inside as well as restrooms and a water fountain. Only endowed members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints can enter past the waiting area.  There is also a temple clothing store near the temple as well as clothing rental inside for members. There are  missionaries on site to answer any questions.< /text>

<Name>Jay Hussein (Jayzakh)< /Name>< Time>
1499631590776< /Time>
< Rating>
5</Rating>
< Review>
This is one of the most beautiful churches in California! There is a lot of areas for photography opportunity. This place is nice as it doesn't have anyone that tries to shoo you out as long as you are being respectful and considerate. Yes that means don't try to do a lingerie shot here!
Anyways you have the front of the church to get right from the get go and then you have small walkways you can walk around the church for different walkways and backdrops of the church. The pure white building makes it so great, On overcast days you kind of have to be careful while taking pictures because it can cause shadows on the models which makes them way too dark to match the church

This place kind of reminds me of a kingdom oblivion for those kingdom hearts fans! Kind of feel like doing a cosplay shoot here!< /Review>

< review>
A beautiful, and spiritual temple, which requires exceptional inspiration to even partially understand.  A temple is place where sacred ordinances take place, something almost completely unknown in these days of general downfall and apostasy, of people and nations.

Over the 50 years of my membership in the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints, I have found that there is a great resistance toward true spiritual values, and an easy acceptance of low, debased thought and action. That is why our nation is drifting in immorality, and unbelief in God and Jesus Christ, and all things of a finer spiritual nature.

But, the scriptures tell us that straight is the way, and narrow is the gate which leads to salvation, and FEW THERE BE THAT FIND IT.  Even my grandfather, a fine man, a Methodist minister, was completely unable to comprehend the deeper spiritual values, and a greater understanding of the gospel of Jesus Christ.  He preached what he was paid to preach.<//review>

< user>
105398138649922666261< /user>
<user_name>Tamara Jessup<//user_name><date>1542514629704<//date>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< text>
A Hind√∫ motel manager motivated me to visit for the first time. He knew that I'm a member of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints, and after I complimented a calendar on the office wall featuring Hind√∫ temples, he enthusiastically told me that he'd visited my beautiful temple! I'd decided not to visit it because I thought I'd feel sad, as I didn't have a temple recommend so couldn't go inside yet. I was wrong. After arising before dawn, I took public transportation (3 buses, 90 minutes) and arrived as many of the temple workers did. I had a warm chat with one and took a few photos. I'm planning another trip when the temporary visitors center is open @ 9. :-)

UPDATE: I have since received my temple recommend and, after receiving my endowments, (during which the dear sister who was my escort was also my mother's proxy), was sealed to my late husband and parents. I was my mother's proxy for her baptism and confirmation as well as her sealing to my father and her parents, and was proxy for one of my late husband's paternal grandfather's wives for their sealing (he remarried after being widowed, but had only been sealed to one of the two). I'm DETERMINED to get familial permission to have his mother's ordinances done so his parents can be sealed and he can be sealed to them (I've had his father's other ordinances done). I have a lot to do for our ancestors!

I could hardly believe it was possible for the temple to be even more beautiful inside than outside, but it is - and, despite being right beside a major freeway, it's as quiet as those who come to such a holy place deserve for it to be. I've learned that two of its architects was a Catholic couple, and it shows. The Bride's Room is so breathtaking that I've sneaked into it a few times to enjoy its beauty and snag a few TicTacs from the bowl on the central table (and the one time I was "caught", we just [quietly] laughed!). I'm blessed to be able to go about one morning a week with sisters in my ward who carpool there to participate in initiatories. I know we retain our free agency after death, just as we had it before and after mortality, and have been blessed with impressions from some of those for whom I've been privileged to be proxy that they had embraced the gospel after death as they were unable to in life, and were grateful for the small, but necessary, role I played in their eternal progression, which was, of course, edifying for me, as well.

While I regret having not lived in such a way so as to be worthy of temple worship for far too many years, I'm grateful that I persevered and made doing so a goal. Having read accounts of the temple experiences of a few women who went on to break their covenants, forsake the restored gospel of Jesus Christ, and withdraw from the Church, I was a little nervous about going, as well as worried that what I'd read would negatively impact my own experiences. But I discussed my fears and concerns with my bishop and had a few chats with the Temple Preparation Class instructor, so nothing I read ended up making any difference to me. I merely feel sad that these women were less prepared, went under questionable circumstances, and therefore couldn't help but interpret the experience far differently.</text>

<rate>5<//rate><text>Rating a Temple experience seems a little odd in a way. For those who are LDS it is an opportunity to go to a place that is peaceful, where you feel the Holy Ghost, or Spirit of God. The San Diego Temple is a very beautiful building inside and out. It has ornate work and the craftmanship is exceptional. All of that is secondary however, to the peace one feels when doing the work of Redeeming the Dead in the House of the Lord and then reflecting on the higher purposes of life. The San Diego Temple is special to me because my wife and I were sealed there in 2000 and we entered an eternal covenant between us and the Lord. All are welcome to the grounds; however, in order to enter the temple and participate in the ordinances of the Temple one must be a member of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints in good standing and have been baptized for at least one year. That is not hard to do, but one should not do it just to enter the temple alone, but because they want a better life, focused on the Savior Jesus Christ.</text><pictures>None</pictures><Response>None< /Response>< Gmap_id>
